"> <span class="comment__author-picture--no-login"></span></div><div class="comment__author-name"> <span class="username">quiltercook</span></div><div class="comment__date"> 20th Sep, 2013</div> </header><div class="comment__text"><div class="field field-name-comment-body field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even">This seems to be more assembly than cooking. How about explaining how to make Piri Piri sauce?</div></div></div></div> </article></div></div><div><div id="comment-wrapper-876966" class="indented"><a id="comment-876966"></a><article class="comment comment__indented-wrapper comment__indented-wrapper-1"><div class=" comment__indented comment__indented-1"> <header class="comment__header"><div class="comment__author-picture"><div class="user-picture"> <img src="//www.bbcgoodfood.com/sites/default/files/styles/avatar/public/pictures/picture-3610491-1415319915.jpg?itok=NZHufq06" width="40" height="40" alt="Shirley Valentine&#039;s picture" title="Shirley Valentine&#039;s picture" /></div></div><div class="comment__author-name"> <span class="username">Shirley Valentine</span></div><div class="comment__date"> 22nd Sep, 2015</div> </header><div class="comment__text"><div class="field field-name-comment-body field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even">Hi, I did leave a recipe I use for a Piri Piri marinade but it seems to have been deleted. If it's of any use, I've posted it again under the questions section (assuming it's still there and not been deleted).</div></div></div></div></div> </article></div></div><div><div id="comment-wrapper-876956" class="indented"><a id="comment-876956"></a><article class="comment comment__indented-wrapper comment__indented-wrapper-1"><div class=" comment__indented comment__indented-1"> <header class="comment__header"><div class="comment__author-picture"><div class="user-picture"> <img src="//www.bbcgoodfood.com/sites/default/files/styles/avatar/public/pictures/picture-3610491-1415319915.jpg?itok=NZHufq06" width="40" height="40" alt="Shirley Valentine&#039;s picture" title="Shirley Valentine&#039;s picture" /></div></div><div class="comment__author-name"> <span class="username">Shirley Valentine</span></div><div class="comment__date"> 22nd Sep, 2015</div> </header><div class="comment__text"><div class="field field-name-comment-body field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even">Although this is a late response, here is an easy piri piri marinade that I got from a TV programme which I find works well:
1-2 tbsp olive/rapeseed/veg oil
Zest and juice of a lemon (or lime)
1 tbsp white wine vinegar
1 tsp smoked paprika
1 tsp oregano
1 tsp chilli flakes or powder (or according to taste)
2 cloves crushed garlic
Mix everything together in a large bowl, add meat, cover, then leave to marinate for as long as possible before cooking. I usually use skinless breasts or thighs to make fajitas, however, you can use drumsticks/thighs as in recipe. Hope this helps.</div></div></div></div></div> </article></div></div></div><h2 class="element-invisible">Pages</h2><ul class="pager unstyled horizontal-elements"><li class="pager-current first">1</li><li class="pager-item"><a title="Go to page 2" href="/recipes/2953680/piripiri-chicken-with-spicy-rice?page=1#c">2</a></li><li class="pager-item"><a title="Go to page 3" href="/recipes/2953680/piripiri-chicken-with-spicy-rice?page=2#c">3</a></li><li class="pager-next bg-turquoise-safe last"><a title="Go to next page" href="/recipes/2953680/piripiri-chicken-with-spicy-rice?page=1#c">next ›</a></li></ul></div></div><div id="fragment-question" class="section-comments__single-tab-content"><div class="view view-comment-views-comment-ajax view-id-comment_views_comment_ajax view-display-id-quest_page view-dom-id-2686d95f9bdb4a6fa66bfe7c5069cd68"><div class="view-content"><div><div id="comment-wrapper-791766"><a id="comment-791766"></a><article class="comment"> <header class="comment__header"><div class="comment__author-picture"> <span class="comment__author-picture--no-login"></span></div><div class="comment__author-name"> <span class="username">jkh</span></div><div class="comment__date"> 30th Aug, 2014</div> </header><div class="comment__text"><div class="field field-name-comment-body field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even">How do you make the marinade for this?</div></div></div></div> </article></div></div><div><div id="comment-wrapper-876961" class="indented"><a id="comment-876961"></a><article class="comment comment__indented-wrapper comment__indented-wrapper-1"><div class=" comment__indented comment__indented-1"> <header class="comment__header"><div class="comment__author-picture"><div class="user-picture"> <img src="//www.bbcgoodfood.com/sites/default/files/styles/avatar/public/pictures/picture-3610491-1415319915.jpg?itok=NZHufq06" width="40" height="40" alt="Shirley Valentine&#039;s picture" title="Shirley Valentine&#039;s picture" /></div></div><div class="comment__author-name"> <span class="username">Shirley Valentine</span></div><div class="comment__date"> 23rd Sep, 2015</div> </header><div class="comment__text"><div class="field field-name-comment-body field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even">Although this is a late reply, here is a quick and easy Piri Piri marinade I use which works well:
1-2 tbsps veg/olive/rapeseed oil
Zest and juice of a lemon or lime
1 tbsp white wine vinegar
2 crushed cloves of garlic
1 tsp smoked paprika
1 tsp oregano
1 tsp chilli flakes/powder (or according to taste)
Simply mix everything in a large bowl, add meat, cover and leave to marinate for as long as possible. I generally use skinless chicken breasts or thighs to make fajitas, however, you can still use drumsticks/thighs as in the recipe. This is usually enough marinade to coat 4 chicken breasts or thighs, but feel free to alter the amount of ingredients according to personal taste. Hope this helps.</div></div></div></div></div> </article></div></div></div></div></div><div id="fragment-tip" class="section-comments__single-tab-content"><div class="comment__no-comments-wrapper"><span class="comment__no-comments-title">Be the first to suggest a tip for this recipe...</span>Got your own twist on this recipe? Or do you have suggestions for possible swaps and additions? We’d love to hear your ideas.<div class="comment__no-comments-sign-in"><a href="/user/login?destination=recipes/2953680/piripiri-chicken-with-spicy-rice">Sign in</a> or <a href="/user/register?destination=recipes/2953680/piripiri-chicken-with-spicy-rice">create your My Good Food account</a> to join the discussion.</div></div></div></div> </section></div></div> <aside class="col span4"><div id="ad-mpu-premium-1-wide" class="ad-mpu-premium-1-wide"><div class="ad ad--mpu-premium-1-wide" id="ad-manager-ad-mpu_premium_1_wide-ba8dc66846"><script type="text/javascript">Drupal.GPT.createSlot("ad-manager-ad-mpu_premium_1_wide-ba8dc66846", function () {var m = Drupal.GPT.buildSizeMapping([[[0,0],[]],[[770,0],[[300,250],[300,600]]]]);var s = googletag.defineSlot(Drupal.GPT.unitPath(), m.define, "ad-manager-ad-mpu_premium_1_wide-ba8dc66846").defineSizeMapping(m.mapping.build()).setTargeting("pos", ["mpu_premium_1"]).addService(googletag.pubads());});</script></div></div><div id="ad-mpu-premium-2"><div class="ad ad--mpu-premium-2-wide" id="ad-manager-ad-mpu_premium_2_wide-fba1aea6ca"><script type="text/javascript">Drupal.GPT.createSlot("ad-manager-ad-mpu_premium_2_wide-fba1aea6ca", function () {var m = Drupal.GPT.buildSizeMa